      "rationale": "NIH predictions compared to FDA benchmark experimental data at all 5 operating points. Mean absolute error 18%, maximum error 24%, both within the ±25% acceptance band for level 3. Confidence in comparison ~50% due to inter-laboratory scatter in experimental NIH measurements (CV ~20% across published FDA benchmark studies). This uncertainty is explicitly incorporated into the comparison metric and does not invalidate the level 3 assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Primary QoI is NIH (normalized index of hemolysis), which is the clinically accepted metric for blood trauma in VAD devices and directly maps to the COU decision threshold. Secondary QoI (shear stress distribution) is also computed and compared. Confidence ~60%; the mapping from NIH to in-vivo hemolysis involves biological variability not captured in the model, and this epistemic gap is explicitly acknowledged. The QoI is nonetheless the best available surrogate and is accepted for level 3."
    },
